[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.
[normal]              
[normal]Ombudsmen and Powers of Own Initiative
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.1
[normal]              
[normal]In the 
[normal]UK
[normal], an 
[normal]Ombudsman
[normal] model has developed which is dependent on the citizen pursuing a complaint.  This is not the model which has developed 
[normal]i
[normal]nternationally where 
[normal]organisations such as the European Ombudsman, 
[normal]have the power to commence an investigation 
[normal]without first receiving a complaint
[normal] 
[normal]from a citizen
[normal].  
[normal]In the 
[normal]Republic
[normal] of 
[normal]Ireland
[normal], the Ombudsman has discretion to commence such an investigation a
[normal]nd this has been used sparingly but to significant effect
[normal].  The value of an ‘own-initiative’ power is that it can deliver systemic improvements for a greater number of citizens and not just the complainant in a particular case.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.2
[normal]              
[normal]The Deloitte Review recommended that the NIPSO have a power to commence an investigation where there is evidence of systemic maladministration.  
[normal]I am pleased to note that the
[normal] 
[normal]OFMdFM
[normal] policy proposals provide for such a power in the 
[normal]proposed 
[normal]N
[normal]IPSO 
[normal]legislatio
[normal]n
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.
[normal]              
[normal]The Reformed 
[normal]Ombudsman
[normal]’s 
[normal]Office
[normal] Relationship with Parliament’s Select Committee
[normal]s
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.1
[normal]              
[normal]Public Services 
[normal]o
[normal]mbudsmen exist to
[normal] provide a
[normal] service
[normal] for
[normal] the citizen, the wider public and Parliament itself.   
[normal]They play a unique role in reflecting to Parliament
[normal] the concerns of the ‘governed’ about the services overseen and provided by Government.  It is important therefore that Public Services ombudsmen have a mechanism for bringing the results of their investigations to th
[normal]e attention of a Parliament or l
[normal]egislat
[normal]ive Assembly.  
[normal]I currently produce periodic case digests and an annual report which I lay before the Northern Ireland Assembly.  The Assembly’s response has been that 
[normal]the relevant
[normal] 
[normal]S
[normal]elect 
[normal]C
[normal]ommittee ha
[normal]s
[normal] invited me to give evidence of the issues raised in the
[normal]se reports.  
[normal]For instance, I have given evidence to the Committee for the Environment on issues arising from complaints to my Office about the planning service and the Committee for Finance and Personnel about complaints relating to public procurement.  I 
[normal]welcome this opportunity to inform the relevant Select Committee about the results of my investigations which may assist a Committee’s deliberations and considerations of related issues, by providing a real time and, importantly, independent perspective on
[normal] the citizen’s experience of public services.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.2
[normal]              
[normal]The role of informing Parliament of the overall outcome and findings of the Ombudsman across his/her range of investigations should be undertaken by a separate Select Committee from the Committee that is s
[normal]crutinising the financial and administrative performance of the Ombudsman’s office. 
[normal]Scrutiny of an 
[normal]o
[normal]mbudsman
[normal]’s performance by a single Select Committee is a necessary role to ensure that 
[normal]the 
[normal]service is operating effectively 
[normal]and efficiently, 
[normal]and is 
[normal]providin
[normal]g an appropriate, 
[normal]proper 
[normal]account 
[normal]of the 
[normal]guardianship of 
[normal]his/her
[normal] remit and expenditure.  I currently do not report directly to a 
[normal]specific 
[normal]Committee in 
[normal]relation to this separate aspect of my role
[normal]. 
[normal]  However, i
[normal]t is proposed that the financial performance of t
[normal]he new 
[normal]NI
[normal]PSO
[normal] be subject to the scrutiny 
[normal]by
[normal] the Audit Committee
[normal] of the Northern Ireland Assembly.  
